Caching: why, and the strategies.

A database query takes a millisecond at best, and hundreds of milliseconds under load. An in-memory cache lookup takes microseconds, three or four orders of magnitude faster. So for any read pattern where the same answer is being computed over and over, putting a cache in front of the database is the single highest-leverage performance change available on AWS. The shape is simple: the application checks the cache first; on a hit, it returns the cached value immediately; on a miss, it falls through to the database, writes the result into the cache, and then returns; so subsequent requests within the cache's T-T-L get the fast path. AWS offers two services. ElastiCache is managed Redis, Valkey, or Memcached: general-purpose, and it works in front of anything. D-A-X, DynamoDB Accelerator, is a write-through cache purpose-built for DynamoDB and only DynamoDB, a drop-in for the DynamoDB client.

The patterns worth knowing are these. Lazy loading, also called cache-aside: the application reads from the cache; on a miss, it reads from the database and writes the result back; the cache holds only what's actually read, and a cache outage just slows things down because it falls through to the database. The downsides: the first request for any key is always a miss, and data can go stale until it expires or is invalidated. Write-through: every write goes to both the cache and the database, so reads never miss data that's been written and the cache stays consistent, at the cost of a double-write on every write, and possibly caching data that's never read. And time-to-live, or T-T-L: every entry carries an expiry, which is the simple bound on staleness, and it pairs with lazy loading to cap how long stale data lives.

Most designs combine lazy loading and T-T-L, which is cache-aside with an expiry; add write-through only where read-after-write on cached data actually matters.
